{"id":"1810.09627","submitter":"Ronaldo S. S. Vieira","authors":"Ronaldo S. S. Vieira, Tatiana A. Michtchenko","title":"Relativistic chaos in the anisotropic harmonic oscillator","comments":"7 pages, 5 figures. Accepted in Chaos, Solitons & Fractals","journal-ref":"Chaos, Solitons & Fractals 117 (2018) 276-282","doi":"10.1016/j.chaos.2018.10.027","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.CD gr-qc physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The harmonic oscillator is an essential tool, widely used in all branches of\nPhysics in order to understand more realistic systems, from classical to\nquantum and relativistic regimes. We know that the harmonic oscillator is\nintegrable in Newtonian mechanics, whether forced, damped or multidimensional.\nOn the other hand, it is known that relativistic, one-dimensional driven\noscillators present chaotic behavior. However, there is no analogous result in\nthe literature concerning relativistic conservative, two-dimensional\noscillators. We consider in this paper different separable potentials for\ntwo-dimensional oscillators in the context of special relativistic dynamics. We\nshow, by means of different chaos indicators, that all these systems present\nchaotic behavior under specific initial conditions. In particular, the\nrelativistic anisotropic, two-dimensional harmonic oscillator is chaotic. The\nnon-integrability of the system is shown to come from the momentum coupling in\nthe kinetic part of the Hamiltonian, even if there are no coupling terms in the\npotential. It follows that chaos must appear in most integrable classical\nsystems once we introduce relativistic corrections to the dynamics. The chaotic\nnature of the relativistic, anisotropic harmonic oscillator may be detected in\nthe laboratory using Bose condensates in a two-dimensional optical lattice,\nextending the recent experiments on the one-dimensional case.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Oct 2018 02:11:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-15"}
